---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="PPP-RTK">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/positioning">Positioning</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>PPP-RTK</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Positioning · Article 5 of 5</span>
        <h1>PPP-RTK</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          PPP-RTK is the convergence of two worlds: the global reach of PPP and the fast
          ambiguity resolution of RTK. By combining precise satellite products with regional
          atmospheric corrections, PPP-RTK achieves centimetre accuracy in seconds to minutes —
          anywhere within a correction network's coverage — without a dedicated base station.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>10 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#why-ppp-rtk">Why PPP-RTK?</a></li>
          <li><a href="#concept">The PPP-RTK concept</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ssr">State Space Representation (SSR)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#convergence">Convergence vs RTK and PPP</a></li>
          <li><a href="#services">Commercial and open services</a></li>
          <li><a href="#limitations">Limitations</a></li>
          <li><a href="#positioning-landscape">The full positioning landscape</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="why-ppp-rtk">Why PPP-RTK?</h2>
      <p>
        RTK and PPP each have a fundamental limitation that the other solves:
      </p>

      <div class="gap-cards">
        <div class="gap-card">
          <div class="gap-method">RTK</div>
          <div class="gap-strength">✅ Fast — centimetres in seconds</div>
          <div class="gap-weakness">❌ Requires local base station or CORS network. Coverage limited to network footprint.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="gap-arrow">+</div>
        <div class="gap-card">
          <div class="gap-method">PPP</div>
          <div class="gap-strength">✅ Global — works anywhere</div>
          <div class="gap-weakness">❌ Slow — 20–60 minutes to converge. Re-convergence after any outage.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="gap-arrow">=</div>
        <div class="gap-card gap-result">
          <div class="gap-method">PPP-RTK</div>
          <div class="gap-strength">✅ Fast AND wide-area</div>
          <div class="gap-strength">✅ Centimetres in seconds to minutes</div>
          <div class="gap-strength">✅ No dedicated base station</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The key insight is that PPP's slow convergence is caused by needing to estimate the
        ionospheric and tropospheric delays from scratch using only the receiver's own observations.
        If a regional network can estimate these atmospheric delays and broadcast them as
        corrections to the rover, the rover no longer needs to wait — it can resolve ambiguities
        almost immediately, just as RTK does.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="concept">The PPP-RTK concept</h2>
      <p>
        PPP-RTK augments the standard PPP correction stream with additional parameters:
      </p>

      <div class="correction-layers">
        <div class="layer layer-global">
          <div class="layer-title">Global layer — precise products</div>
          <div class="layer-items">
            <div class="layer-item">Satellite orbit corrections (δO)</div>
            <div class="layer-item">Satellite clock corrections (δC)</div>
            <div class="layer-item">Satellite phase biases / UPDs (δB)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="layer-source">Source: Global tracking network (IGS, commercial)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="layer layer-regional">
          <div class="layer-title">Regional layer — atmospheric corrections</div>
          <div class="layer-items">
            <div class="layer-item">Ionospheric delay at each grid point (VTEC or STEC)</div>
            <div class="layer-item">Tropospheric zenith wet delay (ZWD)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="layer-source">Source: Regional CORS network (50–500 km station spacing)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="layer layer-rover">
          <div class="layer-title">Rover — what it gains</div>
          <div class="layer-items">
            <div class="layer-item">Ionospheric delay already known → integer ambiguities decorrelated</div>
            <div class="layer-item">Tropospheric delay modelled → fewer filter unknowns</div>
            <div class="layer-item">Phase biases removed → integer ambiguity resolution possible</div>
          </div>
          <div class="layer-source">Result: Fast integer ambiguity resolution → centimetre accuracy</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The critical difference from network RTK (VRS): in PPP-RTK the corrections are expressed
        in <strong>State Space Representation (SSR)</strong> — individual physical components
        broadcast separately — rather than as a single lumped pseudorange correction at a virtual
        station. This allows the rover to use each correction at its correct spatial resolution
        and combine global and regional products optimally.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="ssr">State Space Representation (SSR)</h2>
      <p>
        Traditional DGNSS and network RTK corrections use <strong>Observation Space
        Representation (OSR)</strong> — a single combined correction per satellite at a specific
        location. The rover cannot separate individual error contributions.
      </p>
      <p>
        PPP-RTK uses <strong>SSR</strong> — each error source is estimated and broadcast
        independently. The rover applies each correction at the correct level of spatial detail:
      </p>

      <div class="ssr-table">
        <div class="ssr-row ssr-header">
          <span>Correction</span>
          <span>Spatial scale</span>
          <span>Update rate</span>
          <span>Accuracy</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ssr-row">
          <span><strong>Orbit correction</strong></span>
          <span>Global (same for all users)</span>
          <span>5 – 60 s</span>
          <span>~2.5 cm</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ssr-row">
          <span><strong>Clock correction</strong></span>
          <span>Global (same for all users)</span>
          <span>1 – 5 s</span>
          <span>~75 ps (~2 cm)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ssr-row">
          <span><strong>Phase bias (UPD)</strong></span>
          <span>Global (per satellite)</span>
          <span>30 – 60 s</span>
          <span>&lt;0.1 cycles</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ssr-row">
          <span><strong>Ionosphere (VTEC grid)</strong></span>
          <span>Regional (interpolated to rover)</span>
          <span>30 – 300 s</span>
          <span>1 – 5 cm (short baseline)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ssr-row">
          <span><strong>Troposphere (ZWD grid)</strong></span>
          <span>Regional (interpolated to rover)</span>
          <span>60 – 300 s</span>
          <span>1 – 3 cm</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The rover interpolates the ionospheric and tropospheric grids to its own location using
        a distance-weighted or kriging interpolation. The correction quality degrades with
        distance from the nearest network station — PPP-RTK is effectively RTK that scales
        gracefully rather than cutting off sharply at a maximum baseline distance.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">📡</div>
        <div>
          <strong>RTCM SSR standard:</strong> The SSR correction format is standardised in
          RTCM 10403.3 (messages 1057–1068 for GPS, 1240–1270 for other constellations).
          This enables interoperability between correction providers and rover receivers.
          The Galileo HAS service also uses an SSR-like format defined in its own ICD.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="convergence">Convergence vs RTK and PPP</h2>
      <p>
        The combination of precise satellite products, atmospheric corrections and integer
        ambiguity resolution dramatically reduces convergence time compared to standard PPP:
      </p>

      <div class="convergence-compare">
        <div class="conv-item">
          <div class="conv-method">Standalone (dual-freq)</div>
          <div class="conv-bar">
            <div class="conv-fill" style="width:100%; background:rgba(255,71,87,0.5);">No convergence</div>
          </div>
          <div class="conv-acc">1 – 2 m (floor)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="conv-item">
          <div class="conv-method">PPP float</div>
          <div class="conv-bar">
            <div class="conv-fill conv-animated" style="width:90%; background:rgba(240,165,0,0.5);">20 – 60 min</div>
          </div>
          <div class="conv-acc">5 – 30 cm</div>
        </div>
        <div class="conv-item">
          <div class="conv-method">PPP-AR (no iono correction)</div>
          <div class="conv-bar">
            <div class="conv-fill" style="width:55%; background:rgba(251,191,36,0.5);">10 – 20 min</div>
          </div>
          <div class="conv-acc">1 – 5 cm</div>
        </div>
        <div class="conv-item">
          <div class="conv-method">PPP-RTK (with iono/tropo)</div>
          <div class="conv-bar">
            <div class="conv-fill" style="width:20%; background:rgba(0,212,170,0.6);">10 – 60 s</div>
          </div>
          <div class="conv-acc">1 – 3 cm</div>
        </div>
        <div class="conv-item">
          <div class="conv-method">RTK (fixed, short baseline)</div>
          <div class="conv-bar">
            <div class="conv-fill" style="width:8%; background:var(--accent);">3 – 10 s</div>
          </div>
          <div class="conv-acc">1 – 2 cm</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Why so much faster?</strong> In standard PPP, the ionospheric delay is estimated
          as an unknown — it takes many epochs before the Kalman filter separates it from the
          ambiguity. With PPP-RTK, the ionosphere is supplied externally, so the ambiguity is
          directly observable from the first epoch. This is the same reason RTK converges fast:
          it implicitly cancels the ionosphere by differencing with a nearby station.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="services">Commercial and open services</h2>
      <p>
        Several PPP-RTK correction services are now commercially available or in trial. The
        correction stream is typically delivered via NTRIP over cellular data, or via L-band
        satellite for remote areas.
      </p>

      <div class="service-grid">
        <div class="svc">
          <div class="svc-name">Trimble RTX</div>
          <div class="svc-type">Commercial</div>
          <div class="svc-detail">Global L-band delivery. Fast convergence (≤1 min claimed). Proprietary correction format. Subscription required. Widely used in precision agriculture and survey.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="svc">
          <div class="svc-name">Leica SmartPPP</div>
          <div class="svc-type">Commercial</div>
          <div class="svc-detail">Regional network-based. Rapid initialisation. Delivered via NTRIP. Used in survey and construction machine control.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="svc">
          <div class="svc-name">Swift Navigation Skylark</div>
          <div class="svc-type">Commercial</div>
          <div class="svc-detail">Automotive-focused PPP-RTK. Sub-decimetre in &lt;10 s claimed. Available in North America, Europe and Japan. API-based delivery for embedded systems.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="svc">
          <div class="svc-name">u-blox PointPerfect</div>
          <div class="svc-type">Commercial</div>
          <div class="svc-detail">SPARTN format via NTRIP or L-band. Designed for IoT and automotive. Sub-metre in seconds, decimetre in &lt;30 s. Coverage: USA, Europe, South Korea.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="svc">
          <div class="svc-name">Galileo HAS (Phase 2)</div>
          <div class="svc-type">Free · In development</div>
          <div class="svc-detail">Phase 2 of Galileo HAS will add regional ionospheric corrections on top of the existing global orbit/clock/bias products, enabling full PPP-RTK free of charge globally.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="svc">
          <div class="svc-name">BeiDou PPP-B2b</div>
          <div class="svc-type">Free · Asia-Pacific</div>
          <div class="svc-detail">BDS-3 GEO satellites broadcast SSR corrections on B2b signal free of charge. Covers Asia-Pacific region. Decimetre accuracy after convergence. Available on B2b-capable receivers.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="limitations">Limitations</h2>

      <div class="limitation-list">
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">Coverage boundary</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            The regional atmospheric corrections degrade beyond the network's footprint. At the
            boundary, PPP-RTK behaves like standard PPP-AR — accurate but with longer convergence.
            True rapid initialisation requires the rover to be within ~200 km of a network station.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">Ionospheric scintillation</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            The interpolated ionospheric correction assumes a smooth, slowly varying ionosphere.
            Scintillation — rapid, spatially irregular ionospheric fluctuations — invalidates this
            assumption. PPP-RTK degrades significantly in equatorial regions after local sunset
            and at high latitudes during geomagnetic storms. In severe cases, performance reverts
            to standard PPP float.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">Data link dependency</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            Real-time atmospheric corrections require a continuous data link — cellular NTRIP or
            L-band satellite. In areas without cellular coverage, L-band delivery is available
            from Trimble RTX and Inmarsat. Outages of more than ~60 s degrade to PPP float.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">Receiver compatibility</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            PPP-RTK requires a receiver capable of processing SSR corrections and performing
            integer ambiguity resolution in undifferenced mode. Not all survey or mass-market
            receivers support this. Compatibility depends on both hardware (multi-frequency)
            and firmware (PPP-RTK engine).
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 — Full positioning landscape -->
      <h2 id="positioning-landscape">The full positioning landscape</h2>
      <p>
        Having covered all five positioning methods, here is a complete comparison to help
        choose the right approach for any application:
      </p>

      <div class="landscape-table">
        <div class="land-row land-header">
          <span>Method</span>
          <span>Accuracy</span>
          <span>TTFF</span>
          <span>Infrastructure</span>
          <span>Coverage</span>
          <span>Cost</span>
        </div>
        <div class="land-row">
          <span><strong>Standalone</strong></span>
          <span>1 – 5 m</span>
          <span>Instant</span>
          <span>None</span>
          <span>Global</span>
          <span class="good">Free</span>
        </div>
        <div class="land-row">
          <span><strong>SBAS</strong></span>
          <span>0.5 – 1.5 m</span>
          <span>Instant</span>
          <span>None</span>
          <span>Regional</span>
          <span class="good">Free</span>
        </div>
        <div class="land-row">
          <span><strong>DGNSS</strong></span>
          <span>0.3 – 1 m</span>
          <span>Instant</span>
          <span>Base / CORS</span>
          <span>Regional</span>
          <span class="warn">Low</span>
        </div>
        <div class="land-row">
          <span><strong>PPP float</strong></span>
          <span>5 – 30 cm</span>
          <span>20 – 60 min</span>
          <span>None (RT products)</span>
          <span>Global</span>
          <span class="good">Free – Low</span>
        </div>
        <div class="land-row">
          <span><strong>PPP-AR</strong></span>
          <span>1 – 5 cm</span>
          <span>10 – 20 min</span>
          <span>Phase bias corrections</span>
          <span>Global</span>
          <span class="good">Free (HAS)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="land-row">
          <span><strong>PPP-RTK</strong></span>
          <span>1 – 3 cm</span>
          <span>10 – 60 s</span>
          <span>SSR + iono network</span>
          <span>Wide-area</span>
          <span class="warn">Med – High</span>
        </div>
        <div class="land-row land-highlight">
          <span><strong>RTK</strong></span>
          <span>1 – 2 cm</span>
          <span>3 – 30 s</span>
          <span>Base / CORS</span>
          <span>Regional</span>
          <span class="warn">Med – High</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔗</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Best of both worlds</div>
          <div class="summary-body">PPP-RTK combines PPP's global reach with RTK's fast ambiguity resolution. The key addition over PPP-AR is regional atmospheric corrections that enable near-instant initialisation.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🗺️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">SSR is the architecture</div>
          <div class="summary-body">State Space Representation broadcasts each error component separately — orbit, clock, phase biases, ionosphere, troposphere. The rover applies each at the correct spatial resolution.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⚡</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Fast initialisation</div>
          <div class="summary-body">With atmospheric corrections supplied, the ionosphere is no longer an unknown — ambiguities resolve in seconds to minutes rather than tens of minutes. Same mechanism as RTK.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🌍</div>
          <div class="summary-title">The future of precision GNSS</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Galileo HAS Phase 2 and BeiDou PPP-B2b will provide free PPP-RTK globally via satellite signal. This will bring centimetre GNSS to any receiver without subscription fees or local infrastructure.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section complete -->
      <div class="section-complete">
        <div class="complete-icon">✅</div>
        <div>
          <div class="complete-title">Positioning section complete</div>
          <div class="complete-body">
            You've covered the full positioning spectrum — from 5 m standalone to 1 cm RTK
            and the emerging PPP-RTK paradigm. The next sections cover the protocols that
            carry these measurements and corrections.
          </div>
          <a href="/learn/protocols" class="complete-link">Continue to Protocols →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/positioning/ppp" class="nav-prev">← PPP</a>
        <a href="/learn/protocols" class="nav-next">Protocols →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Teunissen, P. J. G. & Khodabandeh, A. (2015). Review and principles of PPP-RTK methods. <em>Journal of Geodesy</em>, 89, 217–240.</li>
          <li>Wübbena, G., Schmitz, M. & Bagge, A. (2005). PPP-RTK: Precise point positioning using state-space representation in RTK networks. <em>Proceedings ION GNSS 2005</em>, 2584–2594.</li>
          <li>Galileo HAS ICD v1.0. <a href="https://www.gsc-europa.eu/sites/default/files/sites/all/files/Galileo-HAS-SIS-ICD_v1.0.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GSC Europa →</a></li>
          <li>RTCM 10403.3 — SSR message types 1057–1068. <a href="https://www.rtcm.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">rtcm.org →</a></li>
          <li>Banville, S. & Langley, R. B. (2011). Defining the ambiguity. <em>GPS World</em>, 22(4), 18–22.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .learn-container { max-width: 820px; }
  .breadcrumb { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 28px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--text2); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .article-header { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  h1 { font-size: clamp(24px, 4vw, 38px); font-weight: 700; margin: 10px 0 16px; line-height: 1.2; }
  h2 { font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; margin: 40px 0 16px; padding-top: 8px; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .lead { font-size: 17px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 12px; max-width: 720px; }
  .article-meta { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); display: flex; gap: 8px; }
  p { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  ul { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; padding-left: 24px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  li { margin-bottom: 6px; }
  strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }
  a { color: var(--accent2); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px; }

  .toc { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px 24px; margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .toc-title { font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .toc ol { margin: 0; padding-left: 18px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
  .toc li { font-size: 14px; }
  .toc a { color: var(--text2); text-decoration: none; }
  .toc a:hover { color: var(--accent); }

  .callout { display: flex; gap: 14px; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 24px 0; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; }
  .callout-icon { font-size: 18px; flex-shrink: 0; }
  .callout-info { background: rgba(0,153,255,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(0,153,255,0.18); color: var(--text2); }
  .callout strong { color: var(--text); }

  /* Gap cards */
  .gap-cards { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr auto 1fr auto 1fr; gap: 10px; align-items: center; margin: 20px 0; }
  .gap-card { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 16px; }
  .gap-result { border-color: rgba(0,212,170,0.3); background: rgba(0,212,170,0.04); }
  .gap-method { font-size: 15px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .gap-strength { font-size: 13px; color: var(--accent); margin-bottom: 4px; }
  .gap-weakness { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); }
  .gap-arrow { font-size: 24px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--accent); text-align: center; }

  /* Correction layers */
  .correction-layers { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 3px; margin: 20px 0; }
  .layer { padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .layer-global { background: rgba(0,153,255,0.05); border-color: rgba(0,153,255,0.2); }
  .layer-regional { background: rgba(251,191,36,0.05); border-color: rgba(251,191,36,0.2); }
  .layer-rover { background: rgba(0,212,170,0.05); border-color: rgba(0,212,170,0.2); }
  .layer-title { font-size: 13px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .layer-items { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 3px; margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .layer-item { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text2); padding-left: 12px; border-left: 2px solid var(--border); }
  .layer-source { font-size: 11px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); }

  /* SSR table */
  .ssr-table { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2px; margin: 16px 0; }
  .ssr-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 180px 1fr 100px 100px; gap: 10px; padding: 10px 14px; background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 6px; font-size: 13px; align-items: center; }
